  "prompt": "Why is Google Maps accused of deleting Palestine?",
  "response": "Google Maps has been accused of \"deleting\" Palestine by not labeling the Palestinian territories as a country or using the term \"Palestine\" on its mapping platform. Critics argue that this practice effectively erases Palestinian geographic identity and supports Israel's territorial claims. \n\nKey points of the controversy include:\n\n1. Google Maps typically shows the area as \"Israel\" without clear Palestinian territorial boundaries\n\n2. When searching for \"Palestine,\" users are often directed to Israel\n\n3. Palestinian activists and human rights groups have complained that this representation is biased and politically motivated\n\n4. Google has maintained that this is a technical mapping issue rather than a political stance\n\n5. The controversy highlights ongoing tensions in the Israel-Palestine conflict and debates about territorial recognition\n\nGoogle has generally responded that its maps reflect internationally recognized borders and do not represent a political position on territorial disputes. However, the issue remains sensitive and continues to generate debate about representation and mapping of contested territories.",
